//BitterGourd information Bitter Gourd Bitter gourds need continuous watering all through their life cycle. Water is vital for their growth and survival. Inadequate moisture can delay flowering and result in stunted gourds. 5 to 6 hours of sunlight Bitter gourd (Momordica charantia) is an important vegetable crop and is grown for its immature tuberculate fruits which have a unique bitter taste. 6.0 – 6.7 Well drained sandy to sandy loam; Medium black soils Minimum temperature of 18°C during early growth, but optimal temperatures are in the range of 24° to 27° C Bangalore, New Delhi, Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Dapoli, Punjab, Kanpur and Rahuri January to March, June-July Momordica charantia
//chilly information Chilly In average summer weather conditions, they will need watering two to three times a week. Full sun Chilli belongs to family Solanaceae. It is a small, yearly shrub with a straight and branched shoot.Chilli has simple leaves and its flowers are white in color. In India, chilli is also called mirchi,lanka etc. 6.5 and 7.5 Sandy loam Tropical Andhra Pradesh, Maharashtra, Tamil Nadu and Karnataka September to October Capsicum annuum
//Coffee information Coffee 1200 to 1600 mm Full sun Indian coffee is grown mostly in southern states under monsoon rainfall conditions hence it is also termed as “Indian monsooned coffee". All coffee grown in India are grown in shade. Indian coffee has a unique historic flavour and it is considered as an essential spice. 6 – 6.5. Fertile volcanic red earth soil or deep sandy loam. Semi-tropical climate Karnataka, Kerala and Tamil Nadu February - April Coffea
//cotton information Cotton 800 to 1000 mm Full sun Cotton is a soft, fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll, or protective case, around the seeds of the cotton plants.Cotton is an immensely important crop for the sustainable economy of India and livelihood of the Indian cotton farming community. It is cultivated in about 312 lakh hectares across the world and in around 117 lakh hectares in the country. 7.0 to 8.0 Black Soil Tropical Punjab, Haryana, Maharashtra, Tamilnadu, Madhya Pradesh and Gujarat April to May Gossypium
//Lentil information Lentil About 1 inch of water. Full Sun The lentil(Lens culinaris or Lens esculenta) is an edible legume. It is an annual plant known for its lens-shaped seeds. It is about 40 cm (16 inch) tall, and the seeds grow in pods, usually with two seeds in each. As a food crop, the majority of world production comes from Canada and India, producing 58% combined of the world total. 6.0 and 6.5 Sandy Loam Cold (temperate) Bihar, Uttar Pradesh and Rajasthan April Lens culinaris
//Maize information
Maize 5.8 and 6.8 Full Sun Sandy loam, Red soil May to June Sunny A vigorous growing maize plant requires about 2 en dash 3 litres of water per day during peak growing period or an average consumptive use of water varies from 2.5 to 4.3 mm/day. Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Bihar and Himachal Pradesh Maize, also known as corn in the US, Canada and Australia is the most widely produced crop all over the world. Maize have carbohydrate(70%) ,protein(10%) and oil(4%). Zea mays
//Methi information Fenugreek Water the plant with about 1 inch of water per week. Full sun to Partial shade Fenugreek is popularly known as “methi” in India and used as condiments and as a flavoring agent for food preparations.The young pods and leaves are used as vegetable consumed in daily cooking. 6.1 to 7 Loamy or sandy loam soils with good drainage. Moderately cool, frost-free and clear sky Rajasthan, Tamil Nadu, Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Punjab and Uttar Pradesh First fortnight of October, second fortnight of June to July-end Trigonella foenum-graecum
//Indian mustard information Indian Mustard Mustard requires about 31–40 cms of water. Full sun or Partial shade. Mustard has been a traditionally important oilseed crop in the India. It is a major Rabi crop. 6.0 to 7.5 Sandy loam Temperate Rajasthan, Uttar Pradesh, Haryana, Madhya Pradesh and Gujarat October Brassica juncea
//peas information Peas 1 inch of water per week. Full Sun Green Peas, also popularly known as “garden peas” is one of the vegetable crops in India and basically this crop is cultivated for its green pods. Green peas belong to Leguminaceae family. Green Peas are used in vegetable cooking\'s, in soups and frozen canned food as well. 6.5 – 7.0 Fertile, sandy loam that drains well Temperate Himachal Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan, Maharashtra, Punjab, Haryana, Karnataka and Bihar Oct to November, middle of March to May end Pisum sativum
//Pumpkin information Pumpkin Water one inch per week. Adequate sunlight Pumpkin is a popular vegetable rainy season crop in India. The pumpkin belongs to “Cucurbitaceae” family and is grown extensively during Kharif season (monsoon) and summer season throughout India, for immature and tender fruits. 6.0 – 7.0 Sandy loam with good organic matter Minimun temperature of 18℃ at the early stage of its growth. Ideal temperature range is 25 to 28℃ Madhya Pradesh, Chattisgarh, Karnataka and Haryana January to March and September to December Cucurbita
//rice information Rice The daily consumptive use of rice varies from 6–10 mm and total water is ranges from 1100 to 1250 mm. Full Sun Rice is grown almost throughout the year in hot and humid regions of eastern and southern parts of India that receive heavy annual rainfall. Rice is a tropical plant that requires sufficient water to grow well. That is why it is fundamentally a kharif crop in India. 6.0 to 7 Fertile riverine alluvial soil Hot and humid West Bengal, Bihar, Odisha, Uttar Pradesh, Assam and Madhya Pradesh June to July Oryza sativa
//sesame information Sesame Minimum rainfall of 20 to 26 millimeter. Full Sun Sesame is one of the oldest oilseed crops and popularly known as Til or Gingelly. Worldwide, it is used for its nutritional, medicinal, and industrial purposes.In India, the sesame crop can be cultivated as Kharif, summer, and also as semi rabi crop. 5.5 to 8.2 Well-drained, fertile soils of medium texture Daytime temperatures of 25°C to 26.67°F are optimal Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Tamil Nadu, West Bengal, Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan and Maharashtra May to August Sesamum indicum
//Sorghum information Sorghum 450 to 650 mm of water during a growing season. Full sun Sorghum (Sorghum vulgare Pers.), popularly known as jowar, is one of the most important cereal crop in the world. It is a staple crop for human and other animals for food, fodder, fiber, and fuel. The annual area under it ranges between 17 and 18 million hectares and the annual production between 8 and 10 million tonnes. 6 and 7.5 Deep, fertile, well-drained loamy soils Warm conditions Maharashtra, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Gujarat, Rajasthan, Uttar Pradesh (the Bundelkhand region) and Tamil Nadu May and early June Sorghum bicolor
//soybean Information Soybean 450 – 700 mm Full sun Soybean is one of the most grown and used oilseeds. In India, soybean is predominantly grown as a rainfed crop in all the states of Madhya Pradesh. 6.7 – 7.2 Well-drained, Loamy Soil Warm and moist climate .It is mostly grown in monsoon season Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra. Gujarat, Himachal Pradesh, Punjab and Delhi June to October Glycine max
//Sugarcane information Sugarcane 1200 to 3500 mm Full sun Sugarcane is grown as a Kharif Crop. It needs hot and humid climate with an average temperature of 21°C to 27°C.Sugarcane can grow in any soil which can retain moisture. 5 to 8.5 Loamy soil, Black soil Tropical Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra and Karnataka October, February-march, July Saccharum officinarum
//tea information Tea Two or three times per week during the summer, using rainwater whenever possible. Allow the soil to dry slightly between waterings. Full or Dappled sunlight Tea plantation in India has been contributing significantly towards the socio economic development of the people of the tea growing regions of the country. 4.5 – 5.6 Well drained soil 21°C to 29°C is ideal Darjeeling, Tamil Nadu, Munnar, Assam, Himachal Pradesh, Karnataka and West Bengal April to June and October to December Camellia sinensis
//tobacco information Tobacco 61.60 to 152.10 mm Full sun Today, tobacco is one of the major commercial crops grown in India. Various types of tobaccos are cultivated in India for use in tobacco products such as Cigarette, Bidi, Cigar, Cheroot, Hookah, Chewing and Snuff. 5.0 to 6.0 Alluvial soils, black clayey or loamy soils, grey to red soils Tropical, subtropical and temperate Andhra Pradesh, Gujarat, Karnataka, Uttar Pradesh and Bihar December-March, July-September, January-February Nicotiana tabacum
//Turmeric information Turmeric Water it about every two days, and spray it with a mist bottle between waterings. Partial sun Turmeric (Curcuma longa L), the ancient and sacred spice of India known as ‘Indian saffron’ is an important commercial spice crop grown in India. 4.5 – 7.5 Well-drained sandy or clay loam soils Warm and humid climate Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Orissa, Karnataka, West Bengal, Gujarat, Meghalaya, Maharashtra and Assam Mid-December and Mid-March Curcuma longa
//wheat information Wheat 450 to 650mm Full sun Wheat (Triticum spp.) occupies the prime position among the food crops in the world. In India, it is the second important food crop being next to rice and contributes to the total food grain production of the country to the extent of about 25%. 6.0 and 7.0 Loamy soil Low humidity Punjab, Uttar Pradesh, Haryana, Madhya Pradesh, Rajashthan and Bihar October- December Triticum
